-- Stability Contradiction Example
--
-- Demonstrates how contradiction reflects instability:
-- If neg A is unstable (near 0), then A must be stable (near 1).
--
-- This is the stability version of reductio ad absurdum.

-- Postulate: two contradictory propositions at credence c
postulate p : P [ c ]
postulate neg_p : (P -> Empty) [ d ]

-- Contradiction: p and neg_p together force c * d = 0
contradict p neg_p

-- Analysis via stability:
-- - If c * d = 0, at least one of c or d must be "close to 0"
-- - In the Boolean case: either c = 0 or d = 0 (or both)
-- - In the continuous case: the product approaches 0

-- Stability reflection (reductio):
-- - If neg P is Unstable0 (d near 0), then P is Stable1 (c near 1)
-- - This follows from negation flipping stability

-- Therefore: the negation of P has full credence (c = 0 implies 1 - c = 1)
negate sqrt2_irrational from p
